THERE are several senses in which a thing may be said to &lsquo;be&rsquo;
In one sense the &lsquo;being&rsquo; meant is &lsquo;what a thing is&rsquo; or a &rsquo;this&rsquo;
In another sense it means a quality or quantity or one of the other things that are predicated as these are.
While &lsquo;being&rsquo; has all these senses, obviously that which &lsquo;is&rsquo; primarily is the &lsquo;what&rsquo;, which indicates the substance of the thing. For when we say of what quality a thing is, we say that it is good or bad, not that it is three cubits long or that it is a man; but when we say what it is, we do not say &lsquo;white&rsquo; or &lsquo;hot&rsquo; or &rsquo;three cubits long&rsquo;, but &lsquo;a man&rsquo; or &lsquo;a &lsquo;god&rsquo;.
